---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="About · Learning Engineering Commons" active="about">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow">About this site</div>
    <h1>A practice-centered guide, not an exhaustive one.</h1>

    <p>
      This site is a working reference for the emerging field of learning engineering.
      It's organized around the work itself — process, methods, tools, evidence, community —
      rather than around paper taxonomies or citation graphs. The goal is that someone
      arriving cold can quickly see what learning engineers are and what they do, and that
      practitioners can point colleagues here without a long preamble.
    </p>

    <h2>Sources</h2>
    <p>
      Most content is seeded from open, hand-curated registries maintained in this
      repository and from publicly available material on the
      <a href="https://sagroups.ieee.org/icicle/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IEEE ICICLE</a>
      community site. Named practitioners come from a separate study that catalogs people who
      self-apply the "Learning Engineer" title across LinkedIn, ResearchGate, Google Scholar, and
      institutional rosters. Full methodology and caveats live in
      the repository's <a href="https://github.com/wrgr/lecommons/blob/main/titlesearch/PROVENANCE.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener">provenance documentation</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Scope &amp; caveats</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Curated, not comprehensive.</strong> This is a scoped starting point. Sections are deliberately focused; depth grows over time.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>English-language bias.</strong> Non-English title variants, older labels like
        "instructional designer," and government/defense practitioners who aren't publicly
        indexed are under-represented.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>ICICLE is authoritative.</strong> When ICICLE and this site differ on a
        definition or taxonomy, defer to ICICLE.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Links may rot.</strong> External resources change. File an issue if you find one.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Archive</h2>
    <p>
      An earlier version of this project built a large citation graph, concept ontology, and
      broader resource corpus bottom-up. That work lives in <code>archive/</code> in this repo —
      preserved, but no longer the active surface area. If you want the dense graph view, dig in
      there. If you want to understand the field, stay here.
    </p>

    <h2>Contributing</h2>
    <p>
      Suggestions, corrections, and additional resources are welcome. Open an issue or PR in
      the repository. Editorial priorities: keep each section page short, each blurb under three
      sentences, and every inclusion tied to a real practice or community.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .container { padding-top: 3rem; }
  h1 {
    font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 2.4rem);
    font-weight: 500;
    max-width: 32rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  h2 {
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding-top: 1.2rem;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
  }
  ul {
    padding-left: 1.3rem;
    max-width: var(--measure);
  }
  li {
    margin-bottom: .6rem;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
  }
  li strong { color: var(--ink); }
  code {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: .9em;
    background: var(--tint);
    padding: .08em .4em;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }
</style>
